    "answer_id" : 25282857,
    "question_id" : 1001540,
    "content_license" : "CC BY-SA 4.0",
    "body" : "<h2>Java NIO</h2>\n<p>As part of <a href=\"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Non-blocking_I/O_(Java)\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Java NIO</a>, the Java 7 <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/7/docs/api/java/nio/file/Files.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\"><code>Files</code></a> utility type is useful for working with files:</p>\n<pre><code>import java.nio.charset.StandardCharsets;\nimport java.nio.file.Files;\nimport java.nio.file.Path;\nimport java.nio.file.Paths;\nimport java.io.IOException;\nimport java.util.*;\n\npublic class WriteReadUtf8 {\n  public static void main(String[] args) throws IOException {\n    List&lt;String&gt; lines = Arrays.asList(&quot;These&quot;, &quot;are&quot;, &quot;lines&quot;);\n\n    Path textFile = Paths.get(&quot;foo.txt&quot;);\n    Files.write(textFile, lines, StandardCharsets.UTF_8);\n\n    List&lt;String&gt; read = Files.readAllLines(textFile, StandardCharsets.UTF_8);\n\n    System.out.println(lines.equals(read));\n  }\n}\n</code></pre>\n<p>The <a href=\"http://docs.oracle.com/javase/8/docs/api/java/nio/file/Files.html\" rel=\"nofollow noreferrer\">Java 8 version</a> allows you to omit the <code>Charset</code> argument - the methods default to UTF-8.</p>\n<pre><code>Files.write(textFile, lines);\n</code></pre>\n"
  }, {
    "owner" : {
